Exaggerate: The claim exaggerates the extent of the printing error by stating that the ballots "had everything on it" except for the name of Donald Trump.
Contradict fact: The claim contradicts the fact that the printing error affected both Donald Trump and Joe Biden's names, not just Trump's.
Understate: The claim understates the impact of the printing error by suggesting it was a widespread issue when it only affected a single precinct of 2,100 voters out of over 5.6 million registered voters in Los Angeles County.
Lack enough support: The claim lacks sufficient support as the Trump campaign and fact-checking colleagues did not receive a response when seeking evidence to support the claim.
Problematic assumption: The claim makes the problematic assumption that the printing error was intentional or partisan in nature, when it was simply a printing mistake that affected both candidates.
Exist alternative explanation: The claim ignores the alternative explanation that the printing error was a genuine mistake and not a deliberate attempt to exclude Donald Trump's name.
